# Java Solution

```java
class Solution {

    public TreeNode lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode root, TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {

        if(root == null || root == p || root == q)
            return root;

        TreeNode left = lowestCommonAncestor(root.left, p, q);

        TreeNode right = lowestCommonAncestor(root.right, p, q);

        if(left != null && right != null)
            return root;

        if(left != null)
            return left;

        return right;
    }
}
```

---

# Line-by-Line Explanation

### Base Case

```java
if(root == null || root == p || root == q)
    return root;
```

If:

* Tree ends → return `null`
* Current node is `p` → return `p`
* Current node is `q` → return `q`

---

### Search Left

```java
TreeNode left = lowestCommonAncestor(root.left, p, q);
```

Ask the left subtree whether it contains either target node.

---

### Search Right

```java
TreeNode right = lowestCommonAncestor(root.right, p, q);
```

Ask the right subtree the same question.

---

### Both Sides Found

```java
if(left != null && right != null)
    return root;
```

One node exists in each subtree, so the current node is the Lowest Common Ancestor.

---

### Only Left Returned

```java
if(left != null)
    return left;
```

The answer lies completely in the left subtree.

---

### Otherwise

```java
return right;
```

The answer lies completely in the right subtree.

---

# Why Does This Work?

Every recursive call returns one of three values:

* `null` → Neither `p` nor `q` found.
* `p` or `q` → Found one target.
* LCA → Already found in a lower subtree.

The parent node combines the results.

| Left   | Right  | Return                 |
| ------ | ------ | ---------------------- |
| `null` | `null` | `null`                 |
| Node   | `null` | Node                   |
| `null` | Node   | Node                   |
| Node   | Node   | **Current Root (LCA)** |

This combination logic is the heart of the algorithm.

---

# Complexity Analysis

### Time Complexity

```text
O(n)
```

Every node is visited once.

---

### Space Complexity

```text
O(h)
```

where `h` is the height of the tree due to the recursion stack.

* Balanced Tree → `O(log n)`
* Skewed Tree → `O(n)`

---

# Common Mistakes

### ❌ Mistake 1

Thinking "Lowest" means the smallest node value.

Incorrect:

```text
LCA(6,2) = 3 because 3 < 5
```

Correct:

```text
LCA(6,2) = 5
```

"Lowest" refers to the **deepest node in the tree**, not the smallest value.

---

### ❌ Mistake 2

Returning the current node whenever one subtree returns a node.

The current node is the LCA **only when both left and right recursive calls return non-null**.

---

### ❌ Mistake 3

Forgetting the base case.

Always check:

```java
if(root == null || root == p || root == q)
    return root;
```

---

# Pattern Recognition

Whenever a tree problem asks:

* Lowest Common Ancestor
* Common Parent
* Find a node using both left and right subtrees

Think of this recursion template:

```java
left = solve(root.left);

right = solve(root.right);

if(left != null && right != null)
    return root;

return left != null ? left : right;
```

This is known as the **Search-and-Combine Recursion Pattern**.

